dreaming_meta_recipe
  record_type "meta_recipe"
  topic "dreaming"
  title "Dreaming: low-priority memory maintenance and meta-algorithm self-generalization"
  summary "Machine-readable recipe for reproducing the deterministic dreaming planner (issue #540) from src/dreaming.rs. While idle and never blocking the UI, dreaming reads the memory graph and produces a pure plan: it classifies every event by how durable it is, recalculates how often each event is actually used, restructures recomputable duplicates around the most-reused copy, recalculates which topics the user interacts with most, recovers the durable requirements the user stated on those topics, generalizes each requirement into a meta-algorithm amendment so the user never has to repeat himself, reclaims space toward a 20% free-space reserve (issue #494) by forgetting recomputable/refetchable data, and — under pressure — forgets the specific task/test-run records a retained amendment can reproduce while keeping the amendment forever. The recipe is grounded: tests/unit/specification/dreaming_meta_algorithm.rs asserts the live source still defines every function and lists eight contiguously ordered steps, so this file always describes how the running planner was produced, not stale prose."
  generalization "To extend dreaming to a new kind of stored experience, do not add a bespoke branch: make the new behaviour fall out of the eight ordered steps below. Classify the new event class into one DreamingDurability so its recomputability is known, let usage recalculation and duplicate restructuring treat it uniformly, let topic recalculation attribute it to the topic the user cares about, let requirement recovery lift any standing requirement it states, and let generalization bake that requirement into a MetaAlgorithmAmendment whose retained rule can reproduce the specific records it covers. The specific record then becomes data the general amendment subsumes, so under storage pressure it is forgotten first while the generalized meta-algorithm keeps every change that lets it solve the whole task class. This is the issue's core rule: as soon as a generalization works, the specific can be forgotten, yet the general meta algorithm must keep the changes that solve all other tasks."
step_classify_durability
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "1"
  id "classify_durability"
  title "Classify every event by how durable and recomputable it is"
  detail "classify_event maps each MemoryEvent to one DreamingDurability: IrreplaceableRaw user/assistant/system experience, RetainedLearning skill ledgers and meta-algorithm amendments, DeletedConversation events on soft-deleted threads, RecomputableCache public-source/tool output, and RecomputableIntermediate summaries and test-run specifics. Only the reclaimable classes are ever eligible to be forgotten, so raw experience and learning are structurally protected."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_recalculate_usage
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "2"
  id "recalculate_usage"
  title "Recalculate how often each event is actually used"
  detail "usage_counts recomputes, for every event, how many other events reference its id across their searchable text and evidence. Deduplication and pressure eviction are ordered by this recalculated frequency of use, so the most-reused copy is the one retained (issue #540: restructure deduplication by recalculated frequency of use)."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_restructure_duplicates
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "3"
  id "restructure_duplicates"
  title "Restructure recomputable duplicates around the most-reused copy"
  detail "duplicate_key groups recomputable events with identical payloads; the group keeps the copy with the highest recalculated usage and proposes RemoveDuplicateRecomputable for the rest. Duplicates are only ever collapsed among recomputable data, never raw experience or learning."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_recalculate_topics
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "4"
  id "recalculate_topics"
  title "Recalculate which topics the user interacts with most"
  detail "event_topic attributes each event to its most specific stable label (conversation title, demo label, intent, or tool, skipping generic ones), and learn_from_memory ranks topics by recalculated interaction frequency into TopicFrequency records. Topics are the unit dreaming learns about, so effort concentrates where the user actually spends time."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_learn_requirements
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "5"
  id "learn_requirements"
  title "Recover the durable requirements the user stated on those topics"
  detail "requirement_statement lifts a standing requirement from a user-authored event when it carries a durable cue (always, never, must, should, prefer, make sure, ensure, do not), and learn_from_memory aggregates them per topic into LearnedRequirement records with occurrence counts and source event ids. This is how the user's requirements are remembered so he never has to repeat himself."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_generalize_amendments
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "6"
  id "generalize_amendments"
  title "Generalize each requirement into a meta-algorithm amendment"
  detail "learn_from_memory bakes one MetaAlgorithmAmendment per topic that has both a durable requirement and specific task/test-run records the amendment can reproduce. apply_dreaming_plan materializes each amendment as a retained, never-reclaimable meta_algorithm_amendment event (idempotently), so the user's requirement is baked into how similar future tasks are solved — Formal AI changing its own meta algorithm."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_reclaim_free_space
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "7"
  id "reclaim_free_space"
  title "Reclaim space toward the 20% free-space reserve"
  detail "required_reclaim_bytes derives the deficit from the target_free_ratio_percent (default 20%, issue #494), current free bytes, and the next incoming write; the pressure phase then selects the lowest-use reclaimable events until the target is met, reporting requires_bigger_storage when recomputable data alone cannot satisfy it. Garbage collection keeps roughly a fifth of memory free by forgetting only recomputable/refetchable data."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
step_forget_covered_specifics
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "8"
  id "forget_covered_specifics"
  title "Forget the specifics a retained amendment can reproduce, keep the amendment"
  detail "Under pressure the planner prefers ForgetCoveredSpecific: a specific task/test-run record covered by a retained amendment is forgotten before any other recomputable data, because the generalized amendment can reproduce it. The amendment itself is RetainedLearning and never reclaimable, so the general meta algorithm keeps every change that lets it solve the whole task class even after its specifics are gone."
  source_file "src/dreaming.rs"
